15.1.2.        Commercial General Liability Insurance.  Commercial General Liability with minimum limits of $TBD per occurrence (to include contractual liability for liability assumed hereunder) and $10 million in the aggregate; 
15.1.3.        Umbrella Excess General Liability and Auto Liability Insurance.  Umbrella Excess General Liability and Auto Liability insurance with minimum limits of $5 million in the aggregate; the umbrella excess policy must afford coverage equivalent to the commercial general liability coverage required in Subsection 15.1.2. Commercial General Liability Insurance of this Amendment; the policy inception date must also be concurrent with the inception dates of the underlying general liability policy; if vendor maintains commercial general liability coverage that exceeds the minimum limits identified in Subsection 15.1.2. Commercial General Liability Insurance of this Amendment, then Vendor may reduce its umbrella excess coverage limit by the corresponding amount;
15.1.4.        Professional Liability Insurance.  Professional Liability (errors and omissions) with minimum limits of $TBD per claim and $TBD in the aggregate;

12.1	Required Insurance/Amounts. Prior to commencing the Services, Vendor will obtain:
(a)	professional liability insurance with policy limits of not less than $2,000,000 per claim (with a sub-limit of not less than $1,000,000 per claim for intellectual property infringement) and an aggregate of not less than $2,000,000, protecting the Vendor against all claims for loss or damage arising out of any error or omission of the Vendor or the Vendor’s Personnel in the performance of the Services. If this coverage is provided on a claims-made basis, the coverage shall be maintained for a period of two years post completion of all Services; 
(b)	technology error & omissions and cyber liability insurance with policy limits of not less than $5,000,000 per claim and an aggregate of not less than $5,000,000 protecting the Vendor and Vendor’s personnel against claims such as, data security and privacy liability, PCI-DSS breach, network interruption, event management, cyber extortion and media content. If this coverage is provided on a claims-made basis, the coverage shall be maintained for a period of two years post completion of all Services; and
(c)	commercial general liability insurance policy with limits of not less than $5,000,000 per occurrence, aggregate of not less than $5,000,000, protecting the Vendor and the Vendor’s Personnel against all claims for bodily injury including death, personal injury, advertising liability, completed operations, product liability, and property damage or loss, arising out of the operations of the Vendor or the actions of the Vendor or the Vendor’s Personnel.  The policy will:
(i)	name the City and the City’s officials, employees and agents as additional insureds; 
(ii)	include a cross-liability or severability of interest clause or endorsement in favour of the City; 
(iii)	include blanket contractual liability coverage; and
(iv)	Include non-owned auto liability coverage

1. Worker’s Compensation Insurance or similar local scheme in accordance with the statutory requirements of the state(s) or country in which service is to be performed. That policy will provide coverage in the event any employee of Vendor sustains a compensable accidental injury while on work assignment with Jack Morton;
2. Employer’s Liability Insurance in the amount of $500,000 each employee by accident, $500,000 each employee by disease and $500,000 aggregate by disease with benefits afforded under the laws of the state or country in which the services are to be performed;
3. Commercial General Liability insurance written on an occurrence form, including but not limited to bodily injury, premises-operations, property damage, products/completed operations, contractual liability, personal and advertising injury, liquor liability, if applicable, with limits of $1,000,000 per occurrence and $2,000,000 general aggregate, and $1,000,000 Products/Completed Operations aggregate;
4. If Vendor’s creation and delivery of any of the services under this Agreement involves the use of motor vehicles, Commercial Automobile Liability Insurance, including owned, hired, borrowed and non-owned automobile coverage, in the amount of $1,000,000 combined single limit each occurrence;
5. Umbrella Liability on a follow-form or at-least-as-broad basis, with limits of $5,000,000 per occurrence and aggregate in excess of the limits in 2, 3, and 4, above;
6. Professional Liability/Errors & Omissions (E&O) with limits of $5,000,000 per claim and aggregate if the Services performed by the Vendor create exposures generally covered by such a policy. This policy must include but not be limited to coverage for liability arising out of wrongful acts and for contractual liability while providing the professional services under this Agreement;
7. Network Security and Privacy Liability (Cyber) with limits of $5,000,000 per claim and aggregate if the Services performed by the Vendor create exposures generally covered by such a policy. This policy must include but not be limited to coverage for the maintenance and use of Personally Identifiable Information or proprietary or confidential information of Jack Morton or its client, access to software for Jack Morton or client computer systems, websites applications or any other information technology services. This policy must also include Privacy and Security insurance to cover civil, regulatory and statutory damages including
notification expenses as a result of actual or alleged breach, violation or infringement of right to privacy, consumer data protection law, confidentiality, or other legal protection for personal information.
8. Crime (necessary only if vendor will handle assets of Agency, client or IPG): If Vendor’s creation and delivery of any of the services involves handling any assets of Jack Morton or its client, including cash and/or securities: Commercial Crime insurance with limits of $5,000,000 per loss covering Vendor and any of its employees or agents who may collect, disburse, handle, or otherwise have access to or possession of any funds, securities, or other assets of Jack Morton or its employees or its client. Vendor must include Jack Morton as a loss payee as its interests may appear. Coverage must include Vendor’s employees whether on site at Jack Morton’s premises, at Vendor’s premises, or at any other site, and whether acting alone or in collusion with others.
9. Property (necessary only if vendor will have property of Jack Morton, its client or IPG): If Vendor will have property of Jack Morton or its client, all-risk property insurance covering Vendor’s business personal property and property of Jack Morton and its client in its care, custody, and control on a replacement cost basis. Vendor will have its insurer grant a waiver of subrogation in favor of Jack Morton, its client and The Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc.
